  "prompt": "What are the end of service benefits of an ex-president of the USA? How much is the ex-president\u2019s pension? How much is he paid in allowances?",
  "response": "Former U.S. presidents receive a variety of end-of-service benefits following their time in office. Here are the key aspects:\n\n### Pension\nEx-presidents receive a pension, which is currently set at approximately **$226,000 per year**. This pension is provided under the Former Presidents Act and is adjusted for inflation.\n\n### Allowances\nIn addition to the pension, former presidents receive allowances for various expenses. These can include:\n\n1. **Staffing Costs:** Ex-presidents are entitled to funding for staff, which is capped at a certain amount (as of recent years, it is around **$150,000 per year** for staff salaries).\n\n2. **Office Expenses:** They can also receive funding for office space and related expenses, which is capped at around **$500,000 per year** for the first 30 months after leaving office, and then about **$200,000 per year** thereafter.\n\n3. **Travel Expenses:** Ex-presidents are provided with funds for travel expenses related to their official duties, which can vary.\n\n### Security\nWhile in office, former presidents receive Secret Service protection and continue to receive it for a certain period after leaving office. As of a law passed in 2013, former presidents (and their immediate family members) are entitled to lifetime Secret Service protection.\n\nOverall, the specific amounts can vary and may be subject to change based on legislation. The benefits help ensure that former presidents can maintain a level of dignity and security after their terms have ended.",
